'''Menelaus of [[Alexandria]]''' ({{IPAc-en|Àå|m|…õ|n|…™|Àà|l|e…™|…ô|s}}; {{lang-grc-gre|ŒúŒµŒΩŒ≠ŒªŒ±ŒøœÇ ·ΩÅ ·ºàŒªŒµŒæŒ±ŒΩŒ¥œÅŒµœçœÇ}}, ''Menelaos ho Alexandreus''; c. 70 ‚Äì 140&amp;nbsp;CE) was a [[Greeks|Greek]]&lt;ref&gt;[[Encyclop√¶dia Britannica]] &quot;Greek mathematician and astronomer who first conceived and defined a spherical triangle (a triangle formed by three arcs of great circles on the surface of a sphere).&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;  [[mathematician]] and [[astronomer]], the first to recognize [[geodesics]] on a curved surface as natural analogs of straight lines.
